text: You know what bit of EDH whining I'm really getting tired of hearing? "We need to run MLD to deal with mono-green ramp, green just ramps ramps ramps!"

Nature's Lore doesn't magically appear in your hand and cast itself for free. You have to have it, and it puts a land into play that generates a single mana. Same CMC as a Felwar Stone that you're just as likely to have drawn. Veggies is putting two lands into play at the same CMC you can drop a Thran Dynamo

Yes, you can then maybe get more mana off those lands with a Gauntlet in play, and they're less prone to getting popped to hand with Rift or just getting Vandalblasted. Lands are better, but they're not better in a magnitude that justifies the amount of whinging
<@U3L7A68JC>
I'm generally fine w MLD as a wincon too. Games gotta end, and Rafiq wearing three swords dropping an Armageddon makes sense.
You rang, <@U3QMCLQQG>?
Yes. See Dana's comments above. The court will hear oral arguments in 2 minutes
I’m always against MLD without a plan; however the argument I’ve hear that bears weight is green’s specialty of ramp is protected by the social contract of EDH unlike those of other colors.
No one bats and eye if all artifacts are destroyed, but lands get the stink eye, etc.
I honestly feel the best combat Boros has as a set of colors/individually against the ramp of ALL the other colors is land destruction
I mean, Blue gets Artifacts more than land ramp, but same concept. Red and White are really good at breaking those, too
Which further punishes that color pair.
Because of the aforementioned social contract? Yes
Right. Green is at even greater advantage because th resource it’s good at exploiting is protected. Boros can’t ramp outside of artifacts or rituals, so it’s even punished before it gets started.
Agreed
Now I think Boros can get away with color-specific land hate.
Boils, etc.
I like the idea of targeted land removal in most games
If I flip Itlimoc, you have ever right to want to take away Gaea's Cradle from me
As a Boros deck, how do you keep up with that except maybe board wipes over and over again?
You know who bounces back from mld best? The color that can go fetch lands
There’s a ton of ways to deal with a single land
<@U4V5EHQ2G> If they've fetched enough, they have a lower potential to even get the lands they fetch for
I've seen Angry Omnath decks get wrecked by searching too much and then a land wipe happens... Not many lands left in their deck now

text: Slow, but good?
played against a guy with two of those in his pool
it was rough
You’d accomplish the same vs angry Omanth w a Wrath. If they’re out of land proccs aren’t happening
Mending is a half measure in edh. Either do it and win or don’t. But please don’t waste everyone’s time
I should say it feels that way
Having not seen it in edh I may be incorrect

Boros is also good at exiling graveyards etc. and bouncing back is hard to do if they’ve already ramped so hard, etc. That really isn’t the point of the discussion, though. I have no problem with Boros using the tools at its disposal to deal with one of green’s major advantages. But like anything that so affects the board, there has to be a plan and an intent.
I will also note I’ve seen so many shitty MLD casts over the years as tantrums or trolls
So that prob skews my POV
Blind MLD is miserable

I think I told ya'll about the story where I got Iona'd and Armaggedon'd. I almost didn't blame the guy because I was the farthest ahead and honestly, I wound up killing him in the end so he probably didn't stand much chance without those strategies.
Henry makes a fair point re the social contract protecting greens advantage but the parallel to that is no other misplayed sweep shits on the game like mld
Iunno, I have raged over some pretty shitty-timed, thought processed board wipes
Or even counter spells
I completely agree, <@U4V5EHQ2G>. MLD Is valid, but you have to be a player with skill to use it.
That’s where it gets most of the stigma.
MLD should be to buy you time so you can win
Not slow everyone down so you can laugh

Did that destroy Halcypn?

Halcyon was destroyed at the end of the Thran-Phyrexian War, when the Null Sphere was sabotaged so the destructive gasses of the stonechargers (which had been used to kill the armies that were attacking the city) couldn't be stopped. All its inhabitants either died from the gas, or fled to Phyrexia.[1] 
The Caves of the Damned would be discovered millenia later by Mishra and Urza, and renamed by the latter Caves of Koilos.[2]
